Halve, peel and thinly slice the @echalion shallot{1}. Peel the @baking potato{1} and chop into roughly 2cm chunks.

Heat a glug of @oil in a large #saucepan{} on medium heat. Add the @Panko breadcrumbs{20%g} along with a pinch of @salt and @pepper. Stir and cook until the crumbs are golden, ~{3-4%minutes}. Wipe out your pan with some #kitchen paper{}.

> The crumbs burn easily - keep an eye on them!

Once golden, transfer the crumbs to a #bowl{} (you'll sprinkle them on later!)

Add another drizzle of @oil to your saucepan and pop back on medium heat. Add the shallot and cook until soft, ~{5%minutes}. Pour in the @water{250%ml} and @vegetable stock powder{1/2} pot. Stir to dissolve the stock pot then add the potato to the pan. Bring to the boil and then simmer gently until the potato is cooked, ~{12-17%minutes}.

> The potatoes are cooked when you can easily slip a knife through.

Meanwhile, drain and rinse the @sweetcorn{163%g} in a #sieve{}. Roughly chop the @flat leaf parsley{1}(roughly chopped) (stalks and all). Add half the parsley to the saucepan with the potato.

Once the potato is cooked, add the @creme fraiche{100%g} and sweetcorn to the pan along with a grind of @pepper. Stir to combine into the sauce. Add the @baby spinach{125%g} and cook until wilted, about ~{3%minutes}. Bring back to the boil, then nestle the @smoked fish mix{215%g} pieces in to the sauce. Cover with a #lid{}, turn the heat to medium-low and simmer until the fish is cooked, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> The fish is cooked when opaque in the middle.

Season to taste with @salt and more @pepper if needed. Carefully spoon the chowder into #bowls{} (being careful not to break up the fish too much). Sprinkle over the remaining parsley and the toasted crumbs. Enjoy!